what made me a writer.

00:01:17.150 --> 00:01:22.350
A lot of people ask me how I
came to write "Girl in Pieces,"

00:01:22.350 --> 00:01:27.360
which is the story of Charlie
Davis who uses self-harm to cope

00:01:27.360 --> 00:01:29.930
with her intense emotional trauma.

00:01:29.930 --> 00:01:32.000
Does everybody here
know what self-harm is?

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.550
I'm not going to explain it to
you because I don't know who's

00:01:37.550 --> 00:01:41.260
in the audience, but it is
the act of hurting yourself

00:01:41.260 --> 00:01:46.780
to release emotional pain,
and I often tell people

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:52.590
that I gave Charlie my scars, but
I gave her her own story, too,

00:01:52.590 --> 00:01:57.990 position:56%
and the story in this book takes her
from Minnesota to Tucson, Arizona,

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:01.290
where she learns how to
take care of herself.

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:03.920 position:56%
She's homeless when the book begins.

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:06.680
She's briefly in a hospital.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:10.050 position:56%
She's kicked out because she doesn't
have insurance, and then she's put

00:02:10.050 --> 00:02:13.840
on the bus by her mother
to go to Tucson to stay

00:02:13.840 --> 00:02:17.560
with her old college friend, or
her old high school friend, Mikey,

00:02:17.560 --> 00:02:19.950
and it's there that she falls
in with a group of people

00:02:19.950 --> 00:02:22.760
at a coffee house that she
ends up working at and sort

00:02:22.760 --> 00:02:26.420
of learns what kind of
life she wants to lead,

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:30.850
and the book is filled
with some very hard topics,

00:02:30.850 --> 00:02:35.960
and as I've been traveling the
states this year talking to people

00:02:35.960 --> 00:02:39.160
about the book, I've met a lot
of people who have read the book

00:02:39.160 --> 00:02:41.200
and said, "You know, I don't know

00:02:41.200 --> 00:02:44.720
if that really qualifies
as a young adult novel.

00:02:44.720 --> 00:02:46.250
There's addiction in the book.

00:02:46.250 --> 00:02:47.550
There's abuse.

00:02:47.550 --> 00:02:49.160
There's assault," and
they say, "You know,

00:02:49.160 --> 00:02:53.670
I'm not sure I want my kids
reading that," and I respect that,

00:02:53.670 --> 00:03:01.970 position:56%
but my answer to that is, "Don't you
remember high school and growing up

00:03:01.970 --> 00:03:04.220
and how hard it could be?"

00:03:04.220 --> 00:03:06.630 position:56%
And my answer to that is, "You know,

00:03:06.630 --> 00:03:12.520
suicide is the number one
cause of death for teenagers.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:16.250
Why wouldn't you let them read a
book about it so they could learn

00:03:16.250 --> 00:03:20.500
about it and process their
feelings if they had those thoughts

00:03:20.500 --> 00:03:26.070
or if they knew somebody in their
school who had committed suicide?"

00:03:26.070 --> 00:03:33.870
How can you tell a 15-year-old
girl who suffered assault

00:03:33.870 --> 00:03:37.340
that she's old enough to go
through it but she's not old enough

00:03:37.340 --> 00:03:42.140
to read a book about it so that
she can process her feelings?

00:03:42.140 --> 00:03:47.200
Books like these need to be on the
shelf, and they need to be talked

00:03:47.200 --> 00:03:52.180
about because kids who
suffer this stuff need a way

00:03:52.180 --> 00:03:56.950
to process their feelings and
to heal, and they need to know

00:03:56.950 --> 00:04:00.750
above all that they're not alone.

00:04:00.750 --> 00:04:04.540
So I say that I write this
story-I wrote this story for a girl

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:09.130
that I met on the bus when I was
leaving my job at the University

00:04:09.130 --> 00:04:14.110
of Minnesota, and she had
fresh scars on her arm,

00:04:14.110 --> 00:04:16.120
and I didn't say anything to her,

00:04:16.120 --> 00:04:19.760
and I always think I
should have talked to her,

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:23.390
and I should have told her,
"I'm where-I used to be

00:04:23.390 --> 00:04:27.220
where you are right now, and
you're not alone, and I understand,

00:04:27.220 --> 00:04:30.680
and you can talk to me, and
there is hope," but I didn't.

00:04:30.680 --> 00:04:35.240
Instead I went home and I thought
about it, and I wrote a book

00:04:35.240 --> 00:04:40.860 position:56%
to that girl, and ever since I wrote
this book, I get letters from kids.

00:04:40.860 --> 00:04:49.900
I got this letter from a girl named
Lily, and Lily said, "I'm Lily,

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:58.630
and I attend school in Illinois,
